<br>
(I live in Japan, and I'm the proud owner of 2 electronic dictionaries designed for Japanese people.  These are fine for translating... I just type in something, and hold it up for the Japanese person to read... but they aren't learning tools for self-study.  The explanations are all in full-on KANJI, which a Japanese person can understand...but it's Greek to us English-speakers.)<br>
<br>
I found this ad through one of PolyKarbon's posts:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.orbislingua.com/ekfk.htm">www.orbislingua.com/ekfk.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
for the Ectaco Partner EJ400T<br>
but I'm deeply suspicious of it... Anyone here actually HAVE one ?<br>
<br>
I've read too many similar ads that promised their dictionary was ideal for an English speaker.  Later, I'd find out that the look-up menu was in English, but the definitions of words were still based on the premise that the user is Japanese, not American.<br>
<br>
Also, the size of the DISPLAY is a factor we don't ordinarily consider until actually USING one of these puppies.  The ad says &quot;5 lines of text per screen&quot;, which is not alot, compared to the Japanese-users' versions in the same 100-to-300-dollar price range.<br>
<br>
(Forget about using the dictionaries with single-line-of-text displays.  They're basically kids' toys.  Although, they're only about $30....$5 to $10, in Japanese second-and shops.)<br>
<br>
Or, should I save up for a tiny, tiny palmtop PC like the Zaurus ?<br>
<br>
What're YOUR experiences/recommendations ? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dynamiteneon>DynamiteNeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>TBA</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/15/03 12:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1228.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.mangaden.com/pics/junk/b.jpg width=75 length=75></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Decent Electronic Dictionary for English-Speakers ?</span><hr size=1> I use <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.physics.ucla.edu/~grosenth/jwpce.html" target="top">JWPce</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.  It uses the Jim Breen dictionaries for it's files and gives you a nice user interface for reading text and looking up stuff.<br>
<br>
It's great because it runs on regular windows and PocketPC, so you can try it out on your pc before you decide to buy a handheld.  It's about the only reason I bought a pocket pc.  I've tried a few other dictionary programs, and in my opinion, jwpce is one of the better ones.<br>
<br>
If you get a pocket pc, just make sure it has a decent amount of memory since, although the program isn't big, the dictionary files can be.  I think with all the basic dictionary files, it ends up taking up around 30 megs, but you really don't need all the dictionaries I think.  <br>
<br>
The main complaint I've had though with the pocket pc is that the battery life stinks.  I have to always make sure to put it on the charger when I'm done with it or else I'll come back later and the battery is dead.  For some reason, the one I have uses battery life quickly even when I turn it off.  I don't know if that's the case with all of them though.<br>
<br>
I saw the ad for the one you listed too, but it seemed a little flaky to me.  I really liked some of the ones I've seen in Japan, I just don't think they make them for English speakers.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sethness>SethNess</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.fureai-ch.ne.jp/~seth/clearhappy.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/15/03 3:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1228.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Pocket PCs vs. electric dedicated dictionaries</span><hr size=1> I've SEEN pocket PCs like Zaurus (running Linux), but don't know much about them except that they're about 600 bucks.<br>
<br>
Electronic dictionaries, on the other hand, are anywhere from 30 bucks to 300 ... and are GREAT with batteries.<br>
<br>
The ones I have run about a year on 3 AA batteries.  Not bad, eh ?<br>
<br>
To extend the life of your batteries, try turning off the backlighting on your pocket PC.  Backlighting can really eat up alot of power.  (I'm basing this on my experiences with laptop PCs.) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sethness>SethNess</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.fureai-ch.ne.jp/~seth/clearhappy.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/15/03 4:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1228.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> How much did your Pocket PC cost ?</span><hr size=1> Out of curiosity, how much did your Pocket PC cost ?<br>
<br>
Is the OS Windows or Linux ?<br>
<br>
What can it do/not do ? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dynamiteneon>DynamiteNeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>TBA</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/18/03 1:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1228.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.mangaden.com/pics/junk/b.jpg width=75 length=75></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How much did your Pocket PC cost ?</span><hr size=1> the pocket pc I have runs windows ce 2003 I think.  Can't remember exactly which version. <br>
<br>
And yeah, the backlighting is turned down most of the time, but it still tends to run out of power pretty fast.<br>
<br>
The Zaurus is different, as you said, since it runs embedded linux and has the Java runtime on it.  I'm sure there's a few electronic dictionaries for that.<br>
<br>
When I bought mine, it was around $500.  I think you could probably get them for cheaper though if you're just going to use it for a dictionary.   I'm pretty sure you can get some of htem for under $200.  It's a Toshiba e740.  It has a very basic version of windows on it and it came with some of the basic applications like word, excel, outlook, and powerpoint.  Mine has wireless internet access on it, but that definitely gets turned off most of the time since I don't use it for that and it really sucks the battery.  About the only other things I installed on it were a few games and then JWPce. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showPrevMessage?topicID=1228.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showNextMessage?topicID=1228.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1228.topic&index=4><img src=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/addreply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.emailToFriend?topicID=1228.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.threadControl?topicID=1228.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=1228.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://pub25.ezb